  "prompt": "Which is the best book of linear algebra?",
  "response": "The best book on linear algebra often depends on your background, learning style, and the depth of understanding you wish to achieve. However, several books are highly recommended in the field:\n\n1. **\"Linear Algebra Done Right\" by Sheldon Axler** - This book is well-regarded for its clear exposition and focus on understanding concepts rather than mechanical procedures. It emphasizes vector spaces and linear maps over matrix computations.\n\n2. **\"Introduction to Linear Algebra\" by Gilbert Strang** - This book is particularly accessible and widely used in introductory courses. Strang's approach is practical and includes applications throughout, making it easier to see the relevance of linear algebra.\n\n3. **\"Linear Algebra\" by David C. Lay, Steven R. Lay, and Judi J. McDonald** - This text is student-friendly with a clear structure, numerous examples, and applications, making it ideal for undergraduate students.\n\n4. **\"Matrix Analysis\" and \"Topics in Matrix Analysis\" by Roger A. Horn and Charles R. Johnson** - For a more advanced treatment, these books are comprehensive references on matrix theory and linear algebra.\n\n5. **\"Linear Algebra with Applications\" by Steven J. Leon** - This book strikes a balance between theory and applications, and is suitable for undergraduate students who want to apply linear algebra concepts to real problems.\n\nConsider what you're looking to gain from your study of linear algebra\u2014whether foundational knowledge, practical applications, or theoretical depth\u2014to choose the right book for you.",
